This is a copy of libpopt 1.19 (the `popt-1.19-release` tag, 2022-06-07),
vendored from its real, actively-maintained upstream project at
https://github.com/rpm-software-management/popt, except that the build
files have been replaced to fit with distcc's own autoconf/automake setup
and NLS support has been left undetected (distcc does not use it; see
"NLS" below).

It is only built and used as a fallback, when `configure` cannot find a
system libpopt >= 1.7 via pkg-config. If you build distcc on a platform
which already has popt, this directory is not compiled at all. You can
force one path or the other with the `--with-system-popt`/
`--without-system-popt` configure flags (see `configure.ac`).

An earlier version of this fallback tree vendored libpopt 1.7 (recovered
from upstream distcc/distcc's own git history, immediately before
distcc's own maintainers dropped it in their commit `3873de0`) — a
snapshot from roughly 1998-2001. That tree was 20+ years and multiple
major versions behind any current system-installed popt, and was missing
two decades of real bugfixes (e.g. `poptReadFile()`'s file-length/overflow
handling, which needed a hand patch on the 1.7 tree but is already
correctly handled in 1.19 — see `poptReadFile()` in `poptconfig.c`). This
directory now tracks the real popt project's own latest tagged release
instead.

`POPT_VERSION` in this directory records the exact vendored release, so a
future accidental regression back to a stale/wrong copy can be caught
mechanically (see the `popt_version_check` step in `c-build.yml`).

## NLS

This bundled copy has NLS (gettext-based translation) left undetected on
purpose: `HAVE_GETTEXT`, `HAVE_DCGETTEXT`, and `HAVE_LIBINTL_H` are not
probed for by `configure.ac`, so the bundled build always takes the
no-translation code path, matching upstream distcc's original choice for
the 1.7 tree. Likewise `HAVE_ICONV` is intentionally left undetected:
enabling it would require probing for and possibly linking `-liconv` on
platforms where iconv isn't part of the base C library (e.g. macOS/BSD),
which would be a new hard dependency this fork's compatibility policy
asks to avoid — see `doc/compatibility-policy.md`. All other optional
features (`glob.h`-based config-directory globbing, `stdalign.h`,
`secure_getenv()`, etc.) are still detected and used when available,
matching a normal system popt build.

popt's real upstream (no longer distcc's own history) is:
https://github.com/rpm-software-management/popt

